About this hotel

In a riad townhouse within the city's medieval walled medina, this informal, traditional hotel decorated with ornate tiles has views of the Atlas Mountains. It's 3 minutes' walk from Jemaa el-Fnaa, the busy square and marketplace, and 6 km from Marrakesh Menara Airport.

Check-in time: 1:00 PM
Check-out time: 12:00 PM

    Joris Vleminckx3 years ago on Google
    4/5
    Positive:
    I stayed two nights on my own at this property, it was a nice change after 2 days in a hot and noisy hostel! The hotel is beautiful, with a little fountain in …
    Positive:
    I stayed two nights on my own at this property, it was a nice change after 2 days in a hot and noisy hostel! The hotel is beautiful, with a little fountain in the patio and a breakfast room on the top floor. I had a room on the ground floor, so I got a bit of noise from families who killed time in the patio but nothing exaggerated. The hotel is at the end of a quiet alley, so it's very peaceful; I slept very well. My room was clean (I didn't use the daily clean-up service though), mattress and bed clothes were OK and the WiFi and airco worked well. Bathroom was clean and shower had hot water. Breakfast was average: bread, one hot pancake, and just several types of butter and marmalade without any cheese or ham. Good price for a central location. Staff was friendly and helpful (they printed my boarding pass at no cost).
    For those looking for the exact location, it's at the end of the small alley that starts from the main Riad Zitoum el Kdim suk street (walk past the hotel Essaouira, it's not the Riad hotel!), which on its turn starts from the main square (it's the second sidestreet to the left) and very near the square.
    Negative:
    There was a bit of a lingering smell emanating from the bathroom drain. My sink was clogged and didn't drain quickly, after taking out the stop, it worked well.
    WiFi wasn't very fast.

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.

    About this hotel

    In a riad townhouse within the city's medieval walled medina, this informal, traditional hotel decorated with ornate tiles has views of the Atlas Mountains. It's 3 minutes' walk from Jemaa el-Fnaa, the busy square and marketplace, and 6 km from Marrakesh Menara Airport. …

    The down-to-earth rooms come with Wi-Fi, air conditioning and en suite bathrooms; some feature elegant paintwork or lamps. A suite sleeps up to 4 guests.

    A restaurant/cafe offers a terrace with views of the mountains and the medina. There's a courtyard with a fountain. A lounge has a TV. Breakfast and bike rentals are available.
